{"cursor":"55833","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\nThe 'equation of time' is the difference between apparent solar time and mean\nsolar time. At any given instant, this difference will be the same for every\nobserver on Earth. The equation of time can be found in tables (for example, The\n[[Astronomical Almanac]]) or estimated with formulas given below.\n\nApparent (or true) solar time can be obtained for example by measurement of the\ncurrent position (hour angle) of the Sun, or indicated (with limited accuracy)\nby a sundial. Mean solar time, for the same place, would be the time indicated\nby a steady clock set so that over the year its differences from apparent solar\ntime average to zero (with zero net gain or loss over the year). Nautical Almanac 1767\n\nThe equation of time is also the east or west component of the analemma, a curve\nrepresenting the angular offset of the Sun from its mean position on the\ncelestial sphere as viewed from Earth. The equation of time values for each day\nof the year, compiled by astronomical observatories, were widely listed in\nalmanacs and ephemerides.\n","linknr":584,"url":"Equation_of_time","recorded":1362479212,"links":47,"instances":["geometry","astronomy","astronomy","astronomy","mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":["http://www.monmouthshiredfas.org.uk/12%20KWK/KK%20Stuff/Journal.pdf","http://www.monmouthshiredfas.org.uk/12%20KWK/KK%20Stuff/Journal.pdf","http://www58.homepage.villanova.edu/alan.whitman/eqoftime.pdf"],"categories":["Dynamics of the Solar System","Timekeeping","Time in astronomy","Earth phenomena","Sundials","Equations"],"headings":["The concept","Sign of the equation of time","History","Explanations for the major components of the equation of time","Secular effects","Practical use","Calculating the equation of time","See also","Notes and Footnotes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Equation_of_time.svg/310px-Equation_of_tim